1
00:00:28,780 --> 00:00:33,273
<i>It looks like a paradise, but it is the
most treacherous desert in the world:</i>

2
00:00:33,484 --> 00:00:36,920
<i>The Kalahari.
After the short rainy season...</i>

3
00:00:37,086 --> 00:00:40,282
<i>...there are many water holes,
and even rivers.</i>

4
00:00:40,489 --> 00:00:45,391
<i>But after a few weeks, the water sinks
away into the deep Kalahari sand.</i>

5
00:00:45,593 --> 00:00:48,389
<i>The water holes dry,
and the rivers stop flowing.</i>

6
00:00:48,927 --> 00:00:51,690
<i>The grass fades to a beautiful
blond colour...</i>

7
00:00:51,829 --> 00:00:53,888
<i>...that offers excellent grazing for the animals.</i>

8
00:00:54,065 --> 00:00:57,431
<i>But for the next nine months,
there'll be no water to drink.</i>

9
00:00:57,601 --> 00:01:02,230
<i>So most of the animals move away,
leaving the blond grass uneaten.</i>

10
00:01:03,071 --> 00:01:08,405
<i>Humans avoid the Kalahari like the
plague because man must have water.</i>

11
00:01:08,574 --> 00:01:12,236
<i>So the beautiful landscapes
are devoid of people.</i>

12
00:01:12,845 --> 00:01:17,405
<i>Except for the little people
of the Kalahari.</i>

13
00:01:22,751 --> 00:01:27,153
<i>Pretty, dainty, small and graceful,
the Bushmen.</i>

14
00:01:27,421 --> 00:01:30,786
<i>Where any other person
would die of thirst in a few days...</i>

15
00:01:30,956 --> 00:01:34,619
<i>...they live quite contentedly
in this desert.</i>

16
00:01:35,260 --> 00:01:38,354
<i>They know where to dig for roots
and bugs and tubers...</i>

17
00:01:38,530 --> 00:01:41,588
<i>...and which berries and pods
are good to eat.</i>

18
00:01:56,642 --> 00:01:59,110
<i>Of course they know what to do
about water.</i>

19
00:01:59,310 --> 00:02:01,938
<i>In the early morning,
you can collect dewdrops...</i>

20
00:02:02,113 --> 00:02:05,774
<i>...from leaves that were carefully
laid out the previous evening.</i>

21
00:02:10,818 --> 00:02:13,446
<i>Or a plume of grass
can be a reservoir.</i>

22
00:02:13,653 --> 00:02:18,317
<i>If you have the know-how, a clump
of twigs can tell you where to dig...</i>

23
00:02:18,491 --> 00:02:21,754
<i>...and you come to light
with an enormous tuber.</i>

24
00:02:25,062 --> 00:02:29,656
<i>You scrape shavings off it with a stick
that is split for a sharp edge.</i>

25
00:02:29,832 --> 00:02:34,529
<i>You take a handful of the shavings, point
your thumb at your mouth and squeeze.</i>

26
00:02:42,774 --> 00:02:45,674
<i>They must be the most
contented people in the world.</i>

27
00:02:45,843 --> 00:02:49,369
<i>They have no crime, no punishment,
no violence, no laws...</i>

28
00:02:49,545 --> 00:02:52,980
<i>...no police, judges, rulers or bosses.</i>

29
00:02:55,082 --> 00:03:00,576
<i>They believe that the gods put only good
and useful things on the earth for them.</i>

30
00:03:00,853 --> 00:03:03,720
<i>In this world of theirs,
nothing is bad or evil.</i>

31
00:03:05,823 --> 00:03:07,882
<i>Even a poisonous snake is not bad.</i>

32
00:03:08,358 --> 00:03:10,883
<i>You just have to keep away
from the sharp end.</i>

33
00:03:13,662 --> 00:03:17,529
<i>Actually, a snake is very good.
In fact, it's delicious.</i>

34
00:03:17,732 --> 00:03:20,097
<i>And the skin makes a fine pouch.</i>

35
00:03:21,434 --> 00:03:25,369
<i>They live in the vastness of the
Kalahari in small family groups.</i>

36
00:03:25,537 --> 00:03:29,438
<i>One family of Bushmen might meet up
with another once in a few years.</i>

37
00:03:29,607 --> 00:03:32,871
<i>But for the most part,
they live in complete isolation...</i>

38
00:03:33,042 --> 00:03:35,805
<i>...unaware there are other people
in the world.</i>

39
00:03:36,078 --> 00:03:41,515
<i>In the deep Kalahari, there are Bushmen
who have not heard of civilized man.</i>

40
00:03:41,682 --> 00:03:45,447
<i>Sometimes they hear a thundering
sound when there are no clouds.</i>

41
00:03:45,684 --> 00:03:50,552
<i>They assume the gods have eaten too
much and their tummies are rumbling.</i>

42
00:03:50,755 --> 00:03:54,884
<i>Sometimes they can even see
the evidence of the gods' flatulence.</i>

43
00:03:55,391 --> 00:03:57,916
<i>Their language has
an idiosyncrasy of its own.</i>

44
00:03:58,127 --> 00:04:01,583
<i>It seems to consist
mainly of clicking sounds.</i>

45
00:04:07,367 --> 00:04:09,232
<i>They're very gentle people.</i>

46
00:04:09,401 --> 00:04:12,336
<i>They'll never punish a child
or even speak harshly to it.</i>

47
00:04:12,470 --> 00:04:18,202
<i>So the kids are extremely well-behaved.
Their games are cute and inventive.</i>

48
00:04:26,713 --> 00:04:28,202
<i>When the family needs meat...</i>

49
00:04:28,381 --> 00:04:31,872
<i>...the hunter dips his arrow
in a brew that acts as a tranquilliser.</i>

50
00:04:32,084 --> 00:04:35,574
<i>When he shoots a buck, it feels
a sting and the arrow drops out.</i>

51
00:04:35,786 --> 00:04:38,447
<i>The buck runs away,
but soon it gets drowsy...</i>

52
00:04:38,621 --> 00:04:40,645
<i>...and it stops running.</i>

53
00:04:42,591 --> 00:04:45,616
<i>After a while, it goes to sleep.</i>

54
00:04:48,895 --> 00:04:55,162
<i>The hunter apologizes. He explains
that his family needs the meat.</i>

55
00:04:56,801 --> 00:05:01,463
<i>The characteristic which really makes
them different from all other races...</i>

56
00:05:01,637 --> 00:05:04,606
<i>...is that they have
no sense of ownership at all.</i>

57
00:05:05,006 --> 00:05:07,473
<i>Where they live,
there's nothing you can own.</i>

58
00:05:07,642 --> 00:05:10,234
<i>Only trees and grass and animals.</i>

59
00:05:10,444 --> 00:05:14,072
<i>These Bushmen have never seen
a stone or a rock in their lives.</i>

60
00:05:14,246 --> 00:05:17,476
<i>The hardest things they know
are wood and bone.</i>

61
00:05:18,449 --> 00:05:24,079
<i>They live in a gentle world, where nothing
is as hard as rock, steel or concrete.</i>

62
00:05:26,889 --> 00:05:30,823
<i>Only 600 miles to the south,
there's a vast city.</i>

63
00:05:34,193 --> 00:05:37,320
<i>And here you find civilized man.</i>

64
00:05:59,978 --> 00:06:03,209
<i>Civilized man refused
to adapt himself to his environment.</i>

65
00:06:03,414 --> 00:06:06,041
<i>Instead he adapted his environment
to suit him.</i>

66
00:06:06,216 --> 00:06:09,116
<i>So he built cities, roads,
vehicles, machinery.</i>

67
00:06:09,518 --> 00:06:13,543
<i>And he put up power lines
to run his labour-saving devices.</i>

68
00:06:13,787 --> 00:06:15,618
<i>But he didn't know when to stop.</i>

69
00:06:15,823 --> 00:06:18,916
<i>The more he improved his
surroundings to make life easier...</i>

70
00:06:19,058 --> 00:06:21,321
<i>...the more complicated he made it.</i>

71
00:06:21,527 --> 00:06:25,359
<i>Now his children are sentenced to
10 to 15 years of school, to learn...</i>

72
00:06:25,563 --> 00:06:28,861
<i>...how to survive in this complex
and hazardous habitat.</i>

73
00:06:29,532 --> 00:06:33,126
<i>And civilized man, who refused
to adapt to his surroundings...</i>

74
00:06:33,302 --> 00:06:35,792
<i>...now finds he has to adapt
and re-adapt...</i>

75
00:06:36,004 --> 00:06:39,938
<i>...every hour of the day
to his self-created environment.</i>

76
00:06:40,340 --> 00:06:42,068
<i>For instance, if it's Monday...</i>

77
00:06:42,308 --> 00:06:47,040
<i>...and 7:30 comes up, you have to dis-
adapt from your domestic surroundings...</i>

78
00:06:47,212 --> 00:06:51,045
<i>...and re-adapt yourself to an
entirely different environment.</i>

79
00:06:58,486 --> 00:07:02,012
<i>8:00 means everybody
has to look busy.</i>

80
00:07:07,226 --> 00:07:09,887
I've got a good story
about handicapped children.

81
00:07:10,061 --> 00:07:15,190
<i>Handicapped children? No! You don't
recommend stuff you don't...</i>

82
00:07:15,364 --> 00:07:20,390
Sorry. I'll only print sweetness and light,
even if it bores the pants off them.

83
00:07:20,769 --> 00:07:24,760
<i>10:30 means you can stop looking
busy for 15 minutes.</i>

84
00:07:26,905 --> 00:07:29,668
<i>And then,
you have to look busy again.</i>

85
00:07:31,208 --> 00:07:32,607
- Hi, Kate.
- Hi, Pete.

86
00:07:32,776 --> 00:07:35,768
Can you use this about the
teacher shortage in Botswana?

87
00:07:35,978 --> 00:07:37,275
- Good story?
- Yeah.

88
00:07:37,479 --> 00:07:39,845
They'll take anybody
who can read and write.

89
00:07:40,014 --> 00:07:43,574
I don't know. I got bawled out
for writing a story on mugging.

90
00:07:43,750 --> 00:07:48,049
My page should be sweet and light,
like Liberace and Jackie Onassis.

91
00:07:48,621 --> 00:07:51,748
<i>Your day is chopped into pieces.
In each segment of time...</i>

92
00:07:51,923 --> 00:07:56,086
<i>- ...you adapt to new circumstances.
- May I share a table?</i>

93
00:07:56,259 --> 00:07:59,285
<i>No wonder some people go
off the rails a bit.</i>

94
00:08:02,130 --> 00:08:04,757
Does the noise in my head
bother you?

95
00:08:06,033 --> 00:08:07,523
No.

96
00:08:07,734 --> 00:08:11,134
Still got that story about
the teacher shortage in Botswana?

97
00:08:11,303 --> 00:08:14,738
- Yeah. You gonna use it?
- No. Maybe they can use me.

98
00:08:15,907 --> 00:08:20,866
<i>In the Kalahari, it's always Tuesday,
or Thursday if you like. Or Sunday.</i>

99
00:08:21,043 --> 00:08:24,944
<i>No clocks or calendars tell you
to do this or that.</i>

100
00:08:25,380 --> 00:08:29,109
<i>Lately, strange new things
sometimes appeared in the sky.</i>

101
00:08:29,282 --> 00:08:33,013
<i>Noisy birds that flew
without flapping their wings.</i>

102
00:08:45,661 --> 00:08:49,026
<i>One day, something fell from the sky.</i>

103
00:09:03,473 --> 00:09:06,567
<i>Xi had never seen anything
like this in his life.</i>

104
00:09:06,942 --> 00:09:11,605
<i>It looked like water, but it was harder
than anything else in the world.</i>

105
00:09:11,846 --> 00:09:15,804
<i>He wondered why the gods
had sent this thing down to the earth.</i>

106
00:09:20,085 --> 00:09:23,610
<i>It was the strangest and most
beautiful thing they had ever seen.</i>

107
00:09:23,820 --> 00:09:27,051
<i>They wondered why the gods
had sent it to them.</i>

108
00:09:32,861 --> 00:09:37,558
<i>Pabo got his finger stuck in the thing and
the children thought he was very funny.</i>

109
00:09:48,571 --> 00:09:54,974
<i>Xi tried the thing out to cure thongs.
It had the right shape and weight.</i>

110
00:09:55,176 --> 00:09:59,305
<i>It was also beautifully smooth
and ideal for curing snakeskin.</i>

111
00:10:03,781 --> 00:10:07,079
<i>And Pabo discovered
you could make music on it.</i>

112
00:10:08,519 --> 00:10:12,715
<i>And every day they discovered
a new use for the thing.</i>

113
00:10:13,889 --> 00:10:18,587
<i>It was harder and heavier and smoother
than anything they'd ever known.</i>

114
00:10:18,725 --> 00:10:22,023
<i>It was the most useful thing
the gods had ever given them.</i>

115
00:10:22,194 --> 00:10:24,321
<i>A real labour-saving device.</i>

116
00:10:26,130 --> 00:10:29,462
<i>But the gods had been careless.
They had sent only one.</i>

117
00:10:29,633 --> 00:10:33,534
<i>Now, for the first time, here was a
thing that could not be shared...</i>

118
00:10:33,736 --> 00:10:35,727
<i>...because there was only one of it.</i>

119
00:10:42,208 --> 00:10:45,041
<i>Suddenly, everybody needed it
most of the time.</i>

120
00:10:45,211 --> 00:10:48,338
<i>A thing they had never needed before
became a necessity.</i>

121
00:10:48,512 --> 00:10:51,413
<i>And unfamiliar emotions
began to stir.</i>

122
00:10:51,615 --> 00:10:55,345
<i>A feeling of wanting to own,
of not wanting to share.</i>

123
00:11:03,690 --> 00:11:09,490
<i>Other new things came.
Anger, jealousy, hate and violence.</i>

124
00:11:26,005 --> 00:11:27,768
<i>Xi was angry with the gods.</i>

125
00:11:27,941 --> 00:11:30,875
<i>He shouted, "Take back your thing!
We don't want it!</i>

126
00:11:31,076 --> 00:11:32,838
<i>Look at the trouble it brought. "</i>

127
00:11:33,144 --> 00:11:34,771
<i>The gods did not take it back.</i>

128
00:11:35,012 --> 00:11:38,741
<i>He shouted, "You must be crazy
to send us this thing! Take it back!"</i>

129
00:11:39,014 --> 00:11:41,346
<i>Then he shouted,
"Look out! Look out!"</i>

130
00:11:43,185 --> 00:11:47,677
<i>But he spoke too late and
the thing felled his daughter Dani.</i>

131
00:12:04,766 --> 00:12:08,599
<i>Xi carried the thing away
from the shelter and buried it.</i>

132
00:12:22,045 --> 00:12:26,275
<i>That evening, there was no laughter
and no chatter around the family fire.</i>

133
00:12:27,915 --> 00:12:30,975
<i>A strange feeling of shame
had come over the family...</i>

134
00:12:31,218 --> 00:12:33,742
<i>...and they were very quiet.</i>

135
00:12:37,321 --> 00:12:42,258
<i>Xi said, "I have buried the thing.
It will not make us unhappy again. "</i>

136
00:12:57,703 --> 00:13:01,900
<i>That night, a hyena smelled the blood
on the thing, and dug it up.</i>

137
00:13:06,409 --> 00:13:12,346
<i>A bad-tempered warthog chased the
hyena away and it dropped the thing.</i>

138
00:13:16,516 --> 00:13:18,506
<i>The next day, Dani found it.</i>

139
00:13:29,125 --> 00:13:33,753
<i>Her brother Toma heard her playing on it
and said, "Let me try. Let me try too."</i>

140
00:14:12,122 --> 00:14:15,249
<i>That night the family was very unhappy.</i>

141
00:14:22,329 --> 00:14:27,060
<i>They began to talk about this thing.
They did not have a name for it.</i>

142
00:14:27,266 --> 00:14:29,825
<i>They called it the "evil thing."</i>

143
00:14:35,806 --> 00:14:38,534
<i>Gaboo said, "Perhaps the gods
were absent-minded...</i>

144
00:14:38,707 --> 00:14:41,369
<i>...when they dropped
the evil thing on the earth.</i>

145
00:14:41,543 --> 00:14:46,706
<i>They've always sent only good things,
like rain, trees, roots and berries to eat.</i>

146
00:14:46,913 --> 00:14:53,281
<i>We are their children and they love us.
But now they've sent this evil thing. "</i>

147
00:14:57,853 --> 00:15:01,220
<i>Xi said, "The thing does not
belong on the earth.</i>

148
00:15:01,390 --> 00:15:05,188
<i>Tomorrow I will take it to the end
of the earth and throw it off. "</i>

149
00:15:06,693 --> 00:15:10,491
<i>Gobo said, "I think the end of the earth
must be very far.</i>

150
00:15:10,662 --> 00:15:14,154
<i>I think you'll have to walk
for 20 days. Perhaps 40. "</i>

151
00:15:16,033 --> 00:15:19,399
<i>Xi said,
"I will start walking tomorrow."</i>

152
00:15:52,692 --> 00:15:55,819
<i>Two thousand miles to the north
in the state of Birani...</i>

153
00:15:56,027 --> 00:15:58,085
<i>...trouble was brewing.</i>

154
00:16:03,333 --> 00:16:06,961
It's 35 million to combat erosion
in the valley.

155
00:16:07,136 --> 00:16:11,571
- And 6 million for improvement of the...
- Hold it, minister. We can't expect...

156
00:16:49,665 --> 00:16:51,928
Get out. We need the car.

157
00:17:12,381 --> 00:17:16,406
That was Sam Boga's gang.
You said they were in Cabinda.

158
00:17:16,584 --> 00:17:19,779
- That's what I thought.
- How many got away?

159
00:17:19,952 --> 00:17:22,750
There were two jeeps.
Four got away.

160
00:17:22,922 --> 00:17:24,411
- Sam Boga was there?
- No.

161
00:17:24,590 --> 00:17:30,685
This time, he's got to die.
Find him and kill him yourself.

162
00:17:35,931 --> 00:17:37,454
Bring him here.

163
00:17:45,903 --> 00:17:47,962
Where is Sam Boga?

164
00:17:50,841 --> 00:17:53,309
Where is your hideout?

165
00:17:56,479 --> 00:17:59,140
Bring the one in the corridor.

166
00:18:00,348 --> 00:18:01,905
Bring that one.

167
00:18:09,354 --> 00:18:13,914
Where is Sam Boga?
Where is your hideout?

168
00:18:14,058 --> 00:18:15,648
Take them...

169
00:18:17,493 --> 00:18:19,825
...to the helicopter.

170
00:18:27,933 --> 00:18:29,332
They went south.

171
00:18:29,502 --> 00:18:32,231
- I'll direct you from the helicopter.
- Yes, sir.

172
00:18:43,945 --> 00:18:45,571
Gas guzzler.

173
00:18:45,813 --> 00:18:48,474
<i>Four of the eight assassins
got away in two jeeps.</i>

174
00:18:48,648 --> 00:18:52,640
<i>The other four were shot in the
Cabinet room by the security guards.</i>

175
00:18:52,818 --> 00:18:55,752
<i>- Bastards.
- The assassins wore brown T-shirts...</i>

176
00:18:55,952 --> 00:18:58,182
<i>...the trademark
of the terrorist gang...</i>

177
00:18:58,355 --> 00:19:00,254
<i>...led by the notorious Sam Boga.</i>

178
00:19:00,490 --> 00:19:05,948
<i>However, eyewitnesses state Sam Boga
did not take part in the assassination.</i>

179
00:19:06,093 --> 00:19:11,053
<i>It is assumed that he masterminded the
attack, some distance from the capital.</i>

180
00:19:11,230 --> 00:19:13,664
<i>Sources announced
that the assassins killed...</i>

181
00:19:13,833 --> 00:19:17,700
<i>...the ministers of education,
public works and agriculture.</i>

182
00:19:17,869 --> 00:19:22,361
<i>The president, who survived the hail
of bullets with only a flesh wound...</i>

183
00:19:22,572 --> 00:19:25,404
<i>...will be addressing the nation
in a few moments.</i>

184
00:19:31,011 --> 00:19:35,504
We did it! We did it! We got the
president, and five of his ministers!

185
00:19:35,681 --> 00:19:37,978
You didn't, you know. That's him.

186
00:19:38,116 --> 00:19:40,913
It was the will of the Almighty
that I was spared.

187
00:19:41,084 --> 00:19:43,244
We mourn the deaths
of three members...

188
00:19:43,486 --> 00:19:46,249
<i>...of my Cabinet.
We extend our deepest sympathies...</i>

189
00:19:46,421 --> 00:19:49,014
He's lying. We got six.
I saw them go down.

190
00:19:49,190 --> 00:19:53,215
You killed three and wounded five.

191
00:19:53,593 --> 00:19:55,856
And you lost four.

192
00:19:56,194 --> 00:19:59,788
Why do I have to work with
amateurs? Did you get away clean?

193
00:19:59,998 --> 00:20:04,023
Yes, we were in and out in two
minutes. They will never find us.

194
00:20:27,050 --> 00:20:28,449
Attention.

195
00:20:33,821 --> 00:20:36,914
- What happened?
- We ran out of gas.

196
00:20:37,223 --> 00:20:40,555
- How long ago?
- About 15 minutes, sir.

197
00:20:40,759 --> 00:20:42,727
Okay, let's go!

198
00:20:48,565 --> 00:20:50,464
Now, you tell me.

199
00:20:52,401 --> 00:20:54,300
Where is Sam Boga?

200
00:20:56,171 --> 00:20:57,762
Where is your hideout?

201
00:21:04,676 --> 00:21:07,405
Next time you're going
to be a bit higher.

202
00:21:07,578 --> 00:21:11,138
I'll tell you, I'll tell you!
The banana forest at Dumgaze.

203
00:21:12,349 --> 00:21:16,909
I'll tell you, I'll tell you! I'll show you.
The banana forest at Dumgaze.

204
00:21:17,186 --> 00:21:19,448
